# Day 33 – Asset Inventory: You Cannot Protect What You Cannot See | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Unglamorous Work That Makes Everything Else Possible

If I am being honest, asset inventory does not sound exciting. Compared to threat modeling or incident response planning, cataloguing what servers and software you have feels like administrative housekeeping. But the more I worked through today's task, the more I understood why it sits where it does in the RMF — before categorization is finalized, before controls are selected, before any meaningful risk assessment can be complete.

The reason is simple: every security decision made in this project is implicitly a decision about specific assets. The FIPS 199 categorization from Day 29 applies to a system made up of real components. The controls selected in the next phase will be implemented on real infrastructure. The monitoring strategy from Day 30 needs to know what it is monitoring. If the asset picture is incomplete or inaccurate, everything built on top of it is built on a shaky foundation.

NIST SP 800-37 Task P-10 formalizes asset identification as a required output of the Prepare step for exactly this reason. Today I worked through building a complete asset inventory for the OpenMRS deployment at MyClinic — not just listing components, but documenting what each asset is, what data it handles, what its security classification is, and what the consequences would be if it were compromised.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Asset identification in the NIST RMF context covers both the information assets — the data the system handles — and the system assets — the hardware, software, and services that store, process, and transmit that data. CIS Control 1 and CIS Control 2, which address hardware and software asset inventory respectively, align directly with this task and provide practical implementation guidance beyond the NIST framework.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, I worked through the asset inventory systematically — starting with the architecture diagram from Day 17 and building a complete picture of every component, its function, the data it handles, and its security requirements.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most today is the concept of the **attack surface** and how asset inventory defines it. Every asset in the inventory is a potential entry point for an attacker, a potential point of data exposure, or a potential point of failure. The completeness of the asset inventory is essentially the completeness of your understanding of your own attack surface.

An asset that is not in the inventory is an asset that has no controls assigned to it, no monitoring coverage, and no owner responsible for its security. In security terms, it is a blind spot — and attackers are very good at finding blind spots. The history of significant breaches is full of cases where the compromised entry point was something the organization did not know was there or had forgotten about — an old server that was never decommissioned, a cloud storage bucket that was provisioned and forgotten, a third-party integration that nobody had reviewed since it was set up.

That framing transformed the asset inventory exercise from a documentation formality into something that felt genuinely important.

