## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2019 Capital One breach** — which I have referenced before in this project, but today I want to focus on a specific detail that is directly relevant to asset inventory.

The root cause of the Capital One breach was a misconfigured Web Application Firewall that allowed a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) attack, enabling the attacker to query the AWS EC2 Instance Metadata Service and retrieve temporary credentials for an overprivileged IAM role. Those credentials were then used to list and download data from over 700 S3 buckets containing sensitive customer information.

The detail that connects to today's topic: Capital One had over 700 S3 buckets containing sensitive data. Some of those buckets contained data from applications that were no longer active. The breach exposed data across the breadth of that asset landscape because the IAM role the attacker compromised had overly broad access — access that reflected an incomplete picture of which assets needed protection and what level of access each component legitimately required.

An accurate, maintained asset inventory is one of the prerequisites for implementing least-privilege access effectively. You cannot scope IAM permissions appropriately if you do not have a clear picture of which assets exist, what data they contain, and which components legitimately need access to them. Capital One's breach spread across hundreds of assets in part because the access model had not been tightly aligned with a current, accurate picture of the asset landscape.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, maintaining an accurate and current asset inventory — and reviewing it regularly as part of the monitoring strategy — is how we prevent a similar sprawl from developing over time.

