## What I Am Still Thinking About

The asset I am least confident about in this inventory is the clinic workstations — and I think that uncertainty is appropriate, because endpoint security is genuinely the hardest part of this picture to get right.

The technical controls for endpoints — EDR software, full-disk encryption, browser policy, MFA — are well understood and implementable. The hard part is the human layer. A workstation with all the right technical controls is still a vulnerability if the person using it clicks a phishing link, shares their password with a colleague, or leaves an OpenMRS session open when they walk away from the desk.

Endpoint security in a clinical environment has an additional layer of complexity because security friction has a real cost — a nurse who has to re-authenticate multiple times during a busy clinic hour is losing time that could be spent on patient care. The right answer is not maximum friction or minimum friction — it is the right friction, implemented in ways that clinical workflows can absorb without generating dangerous workarounds.

I want to develop a more specific endpoint security standard for the MyClinic context that addresses both the technical requirements and the workflow constraints. That feels like a topic worth dedicating a full day to as the project continues.

